    class PGroup {
        final String name;
        final String city;
    
        public PGroup(String name, String city) {
            this.name = name;
            this.city = city;
        }
    
        @Override
        public boolean equals(Object o) {
            if (this == o) return true;
            if (!(o instanceof PGroup)) return false;
            PGroup pGroup = (PGroup) o;
            return Objects.equals(name, pGroup.name) &amp;&amp; Objects.equals(city, pGroup.city);
        }
    
        @Override
        public int hashCode() {
            return Objects.hash(name, city);
        }
    }

**Reason:**
The default implementation of the .equals() method compares the object references or the memory location where the objects are stored in the heap. Thus by default the .equals() method checks the object by using the “==” operator. Read more on `equals` and `hashcode` functions [here][1]


